{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"bb2441f6-b160-4cad-93c7-2a453a28abce","content":"Use **dotnet-trace** — it's the easiest option for .NET apps and doesn't require installing PerfView or ETW setup.\n\n### Quick steps:\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Install the tool (one-time)\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n\n# 2. Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 3. Collect a CPU profile (30 seconds is usually enough)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** (Diagnostics Hub) or **PerfView**.\n\n### Alternatives worth knowing:\n\n| Tool | When to use |\n|---|---|\n| **PerfView** | Need OS-level + .NET merged stacks, GC analysis |\n| **dotnet-counters** | Quick live triage first (CPU %, GC, threadpool) |\n| **Windows Performance Recorder (WPR)** | Deep OS/kernel-level CPU analysis |\n\n### Pro tip — triage first:\n```powershell\ndotnet-counters monitor -p <PID> --counters System.Runtime\n```\nThis shows live CPU %, thread count, and GC stats so you can confirm it's actually your app before collecting a full trace.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"241509f8-aa21-4413-9055-f9ae1b9de037","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a knowledge question, not a code task.","outputTokens":363},"id":"7abb5c71-79a5-4740-8d1f-ffbd51454616","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:50:35.314Z","parentId":"368a4775-8fe8-4c3a-952b-b91c7b2ca4a4"}
